    <h2 id="misMatch">Appendix One: Possible causes for mismatched spouses</h2> 
    <h3 id="ucf">The consequences of having special characters in an entry</h3>
    <p>Where the GRO Index is difficult to read, our transcribers use the following characters which we call <strong>Uncertain Character Format</strong> (UCF) to indicate, “to the best of their abilities”, what they “think” they can see:</p>
    <dl>
      <dt> <strong><code>_</code> (Underscore)</strong> </dt>
      <dd>A single uncertain character. It could be anything but is definitely one character. It can be repeated for each uncertain character. </dd>
      <dt><strong><code>*</code> (Asterisk)</strong> </dt>
      <dd>Several adjacent uncertain characters. A single <code>*</code> is used when there are 1 or more adjacent uncertain characters. It is not used immediately before or after a <strong><code>_</code> </strong>or another <strong><code>*</code> </strong>.
<br />Note: If it is clear there is a space, then <code><strong>*</strong> <strong>*</strong> </code> is used to represent 2 words, neither of which can be read.</dd>
      <dt><strong><code>[<em>abc</em>]</code> </strong> </dt>
      <dd>A single character that could be any one of the contained characters and only those characters. There must be at least two characters between the brackets. <br />For example, <code>[79]</code> would mean either a <code>7</code> or a <code>9</code>, whereas <code>[C_]</code> would mean a <code>C</code> or some other character. </dd>
      <dt><code><strong><em>{min</em>,<em>max</em>}</strong> </code> </dt>
      <dd>Repeat count - the preceding character occurs somewhere between <em>min</em> and <em>max</em> times. <em>max</em> may be omitted, meaning there is no upper limit. So <code>_{1,}</code> would be equivalent to <strong><code>*</code> </strong>, and <code>_{0,1}</code> means that it is unclear if there is any character.</dd>
      <dt><strong><code>?</code> (Question mark)</strong> </dt>
      <dd>Only used where it is unambiguous that there are no characters in the field, e.g. a missing Volume. The question mark must be the only character in the field.
<br />Note: If it is unclear whether the field is empty or not <code>_{0,1}</code> is used.</dd>
    </dl>

    <p>So, if our transcribers had used one or more of these symbols in the entry for our <em>missing</em> spouse, say, in the <strong>Page</strong>number or the <strong>Volume</strong> number, then this entry will not be “matched” to the spouse that we have already found.</p>

    <h3>The consequences of a miscopied District, Volume or Page number</h3>
    <p class="islet islet--light">You can discover more about these concepts [on our Districts, Volumes and Page numbers page] ( "Districts, Volumes and Page numbers").</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">FreeBMD updates its main databases on an approximately 28-day cycle. During the update all the entries that have been transcribed since the last update are incorporated into the database and made available for you to search. As part of this update-cycle, all the entries are subjected to quality assurance checks and “possible error flagging”. These include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li> checking that the District name and the Volume number are consistent with each other and are valid for the time-frame of that record </li>
      <li> checking that the Page number is within the range of “expected” Page numbers for that event (birth, marriage or death), District, Volume and quarter</li>
      <li>indicating whether that record has been “double-keyed”</li>
      <li> indicating whether there are a “suspect” Districts, Volumes or Page “flags” for that particular record.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>So, if for example, one spouse had the District entered as <strong>Aston</strong> and the other spouse as <strong>Ashton</strong>, or <strong>Chorlton</strong> and <strong>Chorley</strong>, (they were all valid District names at various times), the two spouses would not be “matched” in a search and one spouse <em>may be</em> absent from the Page that the other one is listed on. However, if all the other values (quarter, year, Volume and Page) were the same for both spouses, FreeBMD’s quality assurance checks would have likely “flagged up” possible errors in the District-Volume-Page relationships.</p>
